 normanized or Anglicized pronunciation <i>Wogan</i>. Compare   Cadogan  . In Ireland the name has been Gaelicized as <b>Úgán</b>.","History: A family of this name settled in County Kildare following the Anglo-Norman invasion of the 12th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ogan","meanings":["Irish: of Welsh origin, a variant of   Wogan  , found Gaelicized as <b>Úgán</b>."]},{"name":"Vogan","meanings":["Irish: of Welsh origin, a variant of   Wogan  ."]},{"name":"Cadogan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot.","Welsh (Pembrokeshire and Glamorgan) and Irish (of Welsh origin): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Catgucaun</i>, <i>Catguocawn</i>, modernized as <i>Cadwgon</i>. It is composed of <i>cad</i> ‘battle’ + <i>gogawn</i> ‘honour, glory’. See also   Wogan  . The surname is stressed, like its Welsh original, on the penultimate syllable, hence its occasional development to   Duggan  .","Irish: from <b>Ó Ceadagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ceadagán</i>’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Wogan was born about 1335, in Wales, his father, Thomas Wogan, was 25 and his mother, Margaret Ivethorn, was 37. He married Isabel Landres before 1353. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died before 1376, in Ireland."},"et":{"about 1335–before 1376":"umbes 1335–enne 1376","1335–1376":"1335–1376","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","1354–1422":"1354–1422","1311–1356":"1311–1356","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","abt 1334":"umbes 1334","1335":"1335","before 1376":"enne 1376","1356":"1356","1422":"1422","1300":"1300","1311":"1311","1354":"1354","1376":"1376","before 1353":"enne 1353","about 1335":"umbes 1335","15 February 1357":"15. veebruar 1356","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":